WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:19.071 align:middle line:90%


00:00:19.071 --> 00:00:21.400 align:middle line:10%
>>GEORGE NOORY: Welcome
to "Beyond Belief," I'm

00:00:21.400 --> 00:00:22.200 align:middle line:10%
George Noory.

00:00:22.200 --> 00:00:25.380 align:middle line:10%
We have a very different
program for you today,

00:00:25.380 --> 00:00:26.610 align:middle line:10%
and you will enjoy it.

00:00:26.610 --> 00:00:30.600 align:middle line:10%
Dr. Garrett Lisi with us, a
physicist who kind of went down

00:00:30.600 --> 00:00:32.820 align:middle line:10%
the other path, and
we're going to explain

00:00:32.820 --> 00:00:33.930 align:middle line:10%
why in just a moment.

00:00:33.930 --> 00:00:35.700 align:middle line:84%
Garrett, welcome
to "Beyond Belief".

00:00:35.700 --> 00:00:36.290 align:middle line:84%
>>GARRETT LISI:
Thank you George.

00:00:36.290 --> 00:00:37.090 align:middle line:90%
Good to be here.

00:00:37.090 --> 00:00:39.240 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: This path
that you have chosen

00:00:39.240 --> 00:00:41.580 align:middle line:84%
to go down, as
Robert Frost would

00:00:41.580 --> 00:00:44.340 align:middle line:84%
write, "two roads
diverged in a yellow wood.

00:00:44.340 --> 00:00:46.200 align:middle line:90%
I took the one less traveled by.

00:00:46.200 --> 00:00:48.250 align:middle line:84%
That has made all
the difference."

00:00:48.250 --> 00:00:49.650 align:middle line:90%
I think you took that path.

00:00:49.650 --> 00:00:50.820 align:middle line:90%
How come?

00:00:50.820 --> 00:00:52.900 align:middle line:84%
>>LISI: Indeed, it has
made all the difference.

00:00:52.900 --> 00:00:56.400 align:middle line:10%
It was back in graduate
school in theoretical physics

00:00:56.400 --> 00:00:59.530 align:middle line:10%
that I was really loving
general relativity and particle

00:00:59.530 --> 00:01:00.330 align:middle line:10%
physics.

00:01:00.330 --> 00:01:03.585 align:middle line:84%
And at the same time,
what I was learning

00:01:03.585 --> 00:01:06.474 align:middle line:84%
in particle physics wasn't
geometric the same way what

00:01:06.474 --> 00:01:07.890 align:middle line:84%
I was in general
relativity, which

00:01:07.890 --> 00:01:10.810 align:middle line:84%
is Einstein's theory of
gravity, was geometric.

00:01:10.810 --> 00:01:13.920 align:middle line:84%
And I knew there had to be
some geometric theory that

00:01:13.920 --> 00:01:16.350 align:middle line:84%
would also describe
particle physics,

00:01:16.350 --> 00:01:19.240 align:middle line:84%
but nobody seemed interested
in answering that problem.

00:01:19.240 --> 00:01:21.210 align:middle line:90%
They didn't see it as a problem.

00:01:21.210 --> 00:01:23.250 align:middle line:84%
But clearly the universe
is just one thing.

00:01:23.250 --> 00:01:26.010 align:middle line:84%
I mean, it's right there
in the name, universe.

00:01:26.010 --> 00:01:29.100 align:middle line:84%
So I set about trying to look
for a geometric description

00:01:29.100 --> 00:01:30.450 align:middle line:90%
of elementary particles.

00:01:30.450 --> 00:01:33.565 align:middle line:84%
And the most popular one at
the time was in string theory.

00:01:33.565 --> 00:01:34.440 align:middle line:90%
The whole community--

00:01:34.440 --> 00:01:36.231 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Michio Kaku's
theories too, right?

00:01:36.231 --> 00:01:38.310 align:middle line:84%
>>LISI: Yes, very much
involved in that theory.

00:01:38.310 --> 00:01:41.340 align:middle line:84%
And the whole physics community
in high-energy theoretical

00:01:41.340 --> 00:01:43.454 align:middle line:84%
physics was going into
string-theory research,

00:01:43.454 --> 00:01:45.120 align:middle line:84%
and they were trying
to pull me into it.

00:01:45.120 --> 00:01:47.340 align:middle line:84%
And I took a couple
of courses in it.

00:01:47.340 --> 00:01:49.980 align:middle line:84%
But the more I looked into
string theory, the more

00:01:49.980 --> 00:01:52.360 align:middle line:84%
I just didn't believe that
was the right way to go.

00:01:52.360 --> 00:01:54.390 align:middle line:84%
I thought they had made a bunch
of unjustified assumptions.

00:01:54.390 --> 00:01:56.010 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: So you
didn't believe in it.

00:01:56.010 --> 00:01:57.210 align:middle line:90%
You didn't accept it.

00:01:57.210 --> 00:01:57.600 align:middle line:90%
>>LISI: That's right.

00:01:57.600 --> 00:01:59.220 align:middle line:84%
I was very skeptical
of string theory.

00:01:59.220 --> 00:02:01.303 align:middle line:84%
I thought they were making
unjustified assumptions

00:02:01.303 --> 00:02:03.330 align:middle line:84%
and they were overconfident
in the theory.

00:02:03.330 --> 00:02:04.680 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: And are you still?

00:02:04.680 --> 00:02:07.055 align:middle line:84%
>>LISI: Yes, I still felt that
way even more strongly now

00:02:07.055 --> 00:02:10.580 align:middle line:84%
because it's 20 years
later and the predictions

00:02:10.580 --> 00:02:13.080 align:middle line:84%
they were hoping for-- they
were hoping for super particles.

00:02:13.080 --> 00:02:14.280 align:middle line:84%
They were hoping for
some stringification--

00:02:14.280 --> 00:02:15.090 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Hasn't happened yet.

00:02:15.090 --> 00:02:16.324 align:middle line:90%
>>LISI: --has not happened.

00:02:16.324 --> 00:02:18.240 align:middle line:84%
And so they're getting
more and more desperate

00:02:18.240 --> 00:02:20.640 align:middle line:90%
whereas I'm getting happier.

00:02:20.640 --> 00:02:22.680 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: You may be
the one who was right.

00:02:22.680 --> 00:02:24.825 align:middle line:84%
>>LISI: At least I
wasn't as wrong perhaps,

00:02:24.825 --> 00:02:26.515 align:middle line:90%
which in physics is important.

00:02:26.515 --> 00:02:27.390 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: That's true.

00:02:27.390 --> 00:02:30.210 align:middle line:84%
What is the big
difference between what

00:02:30.210 --> 00:02:32.900 align:middle line:84%
you were going after and what
they've been going after?

00:02:32.900 --> 00:02:35.400 align:middle line:84%
>>LISI: Well, essentially we
are going after the same thing.

00:02:35.400 --> 00:02:37.920 align:middle line:84%
We're going after a
mathematical description

00:02:37.920 --> 00:02:41.280 align:middle line:84%
of the fundamental nature
of our universe, all right?

00:02:41.280 --> 00:02:44.310 align:middle line:84%
It's just we're coming about
it from different perspectives.

00:02:44.310 --> 00:02:46.985 align:middle line:84%
They were coming at it
from a model of, well,

00:02:46.985 --> 00:02:49.110 align:middle line:84%
we can solve these problems
in quantum-field theory

00:02:49.110 --> 00:02:52.710 align:middle line:84%
by having extended particles,
have them be strings

00:02:52.710 --> 00:02:54.570 align:middle line:90%
instead of point particles.

00:02:54.570 --> 00:02:57.420 align:middle line:84%
And by having vibrations
of those strings

00:02:57.420 --> 00:02:59.850 align:middle line:84%
in various shapes,
various dimensions,

00:02:59.850 --> 00:03:03.280 align:middle line:84%
we can reproduce the properties
of the known particles.

00:03:03.280 --> 00:03:04.970 align:middle line:90%
So that's the string model.

00:03:04.970 --> 00:03:08.310 align:middle line:84%
And they can also reproduce
string's description

00:03:08.310 --> 00:03:10.104 align:middle line:90%
of gravity.

00:03:10.104 --> 00:03:12.270 align:middle line:84%
But I was coming at it from
a different perspective.

00:03:12.270 --> 00:03:14.853 align:middle line:84%
I was looking at, OK, we already
have a very successful theory

00:03:14.853 --> 00:03:16.770 align:middle line:84%
of particle physics and
quantum-field theory,

00:03:16.770 --> 00:03:18.780 align:middle line:84%
and we have a very
successful theory of gravity

00:03:18.780 --> 00:03:20.040 align:middle line:90%
in general relativity.

00:03:20.040 --> 00:03:22.590 align:middle line:84%
What's the most
minimal possible way

00:03:22.590 --> 00:03:25.890 align:middle line:84%
without doing any other damage
to the conceptual framework

00:03:25.890 --> 00:03:28.110 align:middle line:90%
to combine the two?

00:03:28.110 --> 00:03:30.960 align:middle line:84%
And the geometry
of particle physics

00:03:30.960 --> 00:03:33.005 align:middle line:84%
is wrapped up in these
geometric objects called

00:03:33.005 --> 00:03:35.490 align:middle line:84%
Lie groups which are these
high-dimensional twisting

00:03:35.490 --> 00:03:36.854 align:middle line:90%
surfaces.

00:03:36.854 --> 00:03:39.020 align:middle line:84%
And you can also describe
gravity during Lie groups.

00:03:39.020 --> 00:03:41.430 align:middle line:84%
So it was when I brought those
two together in a way that

00:03:41.430 --> 00:03:43.800 align:middle line:84%
was copacetic, they
actually matched up

00:03:43.800 --> 00:03:46.110 align:middle line:84%
in this very beautiful
mathematical structure

00:03:46.110 --> 00:03:49.400 align:middle line:84%
that mathematicians are quite
fond of called the E8 Lie

00:03:49.400 --> 00:03:50.530 align:middle line:90%
group.

00:03:50.530 --> 00:03:52.830 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: The Science
Channel talked a little bit

00:03:52.830 --> 00:03:55.580 align:middle line:84%
about your life, so let's
take a look at that.

00:03:55.580 --> 00:03:59.520 align:middle line:84%
>>MORGAN FREEMAN: 400 years ago
the great astronomer Galileo

00:03:59.520 --> 00:04:03.240 align:middle line:84%
Galilee had a
groundbreaking insight--

00:04:03.240 --> 00:04:07.920 align:middle line:84%
nature's grand book is written
in the language of mathematics.

00:04:07.920 --> 00:04:11.460 align:middle line:84%
From that time to this,
scientific geniuses

00:04:11.460 --> 00:04:14.160 align:middle line:84%
like Newton and
Einstein used math

00:04:14.160 --> 00:04:17.010 align:middle line:84%
to dig deep into the
working of nature.

00:04:17.010 --> 00:04:20.505 align:middle line:84%
The latest mind hoping to
join these illustrious ranks

00:04:20.505 --> 00:04:22.590 align:middle line:90%
is Garrett Lisi.

00:04:22.590 --> 00:04:24.960 align:middle line:84%
>>LISI: The universe
can very successfully

00:04:24.960 --> 00:04:27.000 align:middle line:90%
be described mathematically.

00:04:27.000 --> 00:04:29.430 align:middle line:84%
You have to imagine
how the world's working

00:04:29.430 --> 00:04:31.380 align:middle line:84%
in certain
circumstances and then

00:04:31.380 --> 00:04:35.990 align:middle line:84%
use reason and mathematics to
develop a description of how

00:04:35.990 --> 00:04:36.990 align:middle line:90%
that might be happening.

00:04:36.990 --> 00:04:41.834 align:middle line:84%
But it's imagination that breaks
a trail before reason enters.

00:04:41.834 --> 00:04:44.520 align:middle line:84%
>>FREEMAN: After
earning his PhD,

00:04:44.520 --> 00:04:49.280 align:middle line:84%
Garrett escaped the confines of
academia in search of adventure

00:04:49.280 --> 00:04:51.290 align:middle line:90%
and a space in which to think.

00:04:51.290 --> 00:04:55.020 align:middle line:84%
>>LISI: Rather than go into
a normal academic-track job,

00:04:55.020 --> 00:04:58.170 align:middle line:84%
I just split off for
Maui, became a surf bum,

00:04:58.170 --> 00:05:00.830 align:middle line:84%
and did the research
I wanted to.

00:05:00.830 --> 00:05:03.818 align:middle line:84%
Mostly spent time doing
physics research and surfing.

00:05:03.818 --> 00:05:07.860 align:middle line:90%


00:05:07.860 --> 00:05:09.420 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Interesting
life Garrett.

00:05:09.420 --> 00:05:12.060 align:middle line:84%
>>LISI: Yeah, I pretty much
BASE jumped off the ivory tower.

00:05:12.060 --> 00:05:12.940 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Just about.

00:05:12.940 --> 00:05:13.740 align:middle line:90%
>>LISI: Yeah.

00:05:13.740 --> 00:05:17.410 align:middle line:84%
I was doing quite well in
school all the way through it.

00:05:17.410 --> 00:05:19.140 align:middle line:90%
I got my PhD.

00:05:19.140 --> 00:05:21.020 align:middle line:84%
And instead of going
to get a postdoc--

00:05:21.020 --> 00:05:22.960 align:middle line:84%
the only postdocs available were
in string theory at the time,

00:05:22.960 --> 00:05:25.030 align:middle line:84%
and I wasn't interested
in going that way.

00:05:25.030 --> 00:05:29.110 align:middle line:84%
So I had saved up some
money during graduate school

00:05:29.110 --> 00:05:30.490 align:middle line:90%
by investing.

00:05:30.490 --> 00:05:32.470 align:middle line:90%
And I wasn't spending very much.

00:05:32.470 --> 00:05:34.810 align:middle line:84%
And so I was to a postdoc--
used to a graduate-student

00:05:34.810 --> 00:05:35.800 align:middle line:90%
lifestyle.

00:05:35.800 --> 00:05:38.260 align:middle line:84%
So I took off for Maui
and became a surf bum,

00:05:38.260 --> 00:05:40.900 align:middle line:84%
learned to windsurf, and worked
on the physics I wanted to.

00:05:40.900 --> 00:05:42.890 align:middle line:84%
It was kind of a crazy
decision to make,

00:05:42.890 --> 00:05:44.400 align:middle line:90%
but it has gone really well.

00:05:44.400 --> 00:05:45.775 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Well I
was going to say,

00:05:45.775 --> 00:05:47.230 align:middle line:90%
you somehow combined both--

00:05:47.230 --> 00:05:48.730 align:middle line:84%
and we'll get into
that a little bit

00:05:48.730 --> 00:05:52.000 align:middle line:84%
later on-- because it
worked for you, didn't it?

00:05:52.000 --> 00:05:53.300 align:middle line:90%
>>LISI: I got really lucky.

00:05:53.300 --> 00:05:54.841 align:middle line:84%
I don't know how
else to describe it.

00:05:54.841 --> 00:05:57.070 align:middle line:84%
I seem to have gotten
lucky my whole life

00:05:57.070 --> 00:06:00.160 align:middle line:84%
both with my investments,
with my research in physics.

00:06:00.160 --> 00:06:02.319 align:middle line:84%
And it's hard not to
get lucky when you're

00:06:02.319 --> 00:06:03.610 align:middle line:90%
spending a lot of time surfing.

00:06:03.610 --> 00:06:07.900 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: As a physicist today,
what are you looking for?

00:06:07.900 --> 00:06:10.180 align:middle line:84%
What answers are
you trying to seek?

00:06:10.180 --> 00:06:12.280 align:middle line:84%
>>LISI: Well, the whole
reason I got into physics

00:06:12.280 --> 00:06:14.440 align:middle line:84%
is to figure out
what this universe is

00:06:14.440 --> 00:06:16.870 align:middle line:90%
that we're in, fundamentally.

00:06:16.870 --> 00:06:19.750 align:middle line:84%
And when I found
out as a young man

00:06:19.750 --> 00:06:21.760 align:middle line:84%
that the mathematics I
was learning and really

00:06:21.760 --> 00:06:24.040 align:middle line:84%
enjoying in an
abstract way actually

00:06:24.040 --> 00:06:26.020 align:middle line:84%
applies to describe
how our universe

00:06:26.020 --> 00:06:30.880 align:middle line:84%
functions, on a very
deep level it was just

00:06:30.880 --> 00:06:32.320 align:middle line:90%
intoxicating and addicting.

00:06:32.320 --> 00:06:35.710 align:middle line:84%
And I just became obsessed
with the puzzle of figuring out

00:06:35.710 --> 00:06:37.730 align:middle line:84%
how our universe
works mathematically

00:06:37.730 --> 00:06:38.530 align:middle line:90%
and fundamentally.

00:06:38.530 --> 00:06:40.060 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: All right,
I'm going to ask

00:06:40.060 --> 00:06:43.540 align:middle line:84%
you some nonphysics-type
questions

00:06:43.540 --> 00:06:46.600 align:middle line:84%
because we're not physicists
and most of us watching

00:06:46.600 --> 00:06:49.960 align:middle line:84%
aren't, but maybe you can
explain it to us in terms

00:06:49.960 --> 00:06:51.580 align:middle line:90%
that we would understand.

00:06:51.580 --> 00:06:55.750 align:middle line:90%
What the heck is the Big Bang?

00:06:55.750 --> 00:06:58.810 align:middle line:84%
Haven't found one
explanation yet in the years

00:06:58.810 --> 00:07:01.360 align:middle line:84%
I've been doing "Coast to
Coast" and "Beyond Belief",

00:07:01.360 --> 00:07:03.730 align:middle line:84%
I have not gotten
one explanation

00:07:03.730 --> 00:07:05.140 align:middle line:90%
that makes sense to me.

00:07:05.140 --> 00:07:07.880 align:middle line:84%
>>LISI: All right,
well, I'll do my best.

00:07:07.880 --> 00:07:10.630 align:middle line:84%
I can start out by
telling you what it isn't.

00:07:10.630 --> 00:07:13.240 align:middle line:84%
The Big Bang is not
an explosion of matter

00:07:13.240 --> 00:07:14.750 align:middle line:90%
from a point in space.

00:07:14.750 --> 00:07:18.580 align:middle line:84%
What the Big Bang is is we
look out into the cosmos

00:07:18.580 --> 00:07:23.390 align:middle line:84%
and we see distant galaxies
moving away from us.

00:07:23.390 --> 00:07:25.600 align:middle line:84%
And not only are they
moving away from us

00:07:25.600 --> 00:07:28.270 align:middle line:84%
but they're moving away from
us at an accelerating rate.

00:07:28.270 --> 00:07:29.770 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Aren't we
moving with them?

00:07:29.770 --> 00:07:30.853 align:middle line:90%
>>LISI: We're also moving.

00:07:30.853 --> 00:07:36.020 align:middle line:84%
So it's as if everything
is moving away from itself.

00:07:36.020 --> 00:07:38.510 align:middle line:84%
So the entire
universe is expanding,

00:07:38.510 --> 00:07:40.680 align:middle line:84%
and that expansion
is accelerating.

00:07:40.680 --> 00:07:43.220 align:middle line:84%
So the main idea of
the Big Bang is, well,

00:07:43.220 --> 00:07:46.400 align:middle line:90%
if you look back in time--

00:07:46.400 --> 00:07:47.790 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: If it was going out.

00:07:47.790 --> 00:07:48.940 align:middle line:84%
>>LISI: --if it's
going out now--

00:07:48.940 --> 00:07:50.606 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Then somehow
it came in, right?

00:07:50.606 --> 00:07:52.850 align:middle line:84%
>>LISI: Right, then
we know it came

00:07:52.850 --> 00:07:55.772 align:middle line:84%
from all being very
compressed and hot together.

00:07:55.772 --> 00:07:57.230 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Logic
would tell you that.

00:07:57.230 --> 00:07:57.530 align:middle line:90%
>>LISI: Yes.

00:07:57.530 --> 00:07:58.530 align:middle line:90%
And it's not just logic.

00:07:58.530 --> 00:08:00.900 align:middle line:84%
We also have Einstein's
theory of general relativity,

00:08:00.900 --> 00:08:02.360 align:middle line:90%
which describes gravity.

00:08:02.360 --> 00:08:07.190 align:middle line:84%
And Einstein describes
this expanding universe

00:08:07.190 --> 00:08:11.600 align:middle line:84%
as an expanding fabric
of space itself.

00:08:11.600 --> 00:08:12.830 align:middle line:90%
And it looks like--

00:08:12.830 --> 00:08:14.540 align:middle line:84%
I mean, we're not
at the center of it

00:08:14.540 --> 00:08:16.430 align:middle line:90%
because there is no center.

00:08:16.430 --> 00:08:19.760 align:middle line:84%
In fact, it appears to be
an infinitely flat expanse

00:08:19.760 --> 00:08:22.700 align:middle line:84%
of space that is
expanding, and our place

00:08:22.700 --> 00:08:26.360 align:middle line:84%
in it of the Milky Way
is not at all special.

00:08:26.360 --> 00:08:28.790 align:middle line:84%
But since it's the
space itself that

00:08:28.790 --> 00:08:30.980 align:middle line:84%
seems to be expanding,
from our perspective

00:08:30.980 --> 00:08:34.070 align:middle line:84%
it just looks like everything
is expanding away from us.

00:08:34.070 --> 00:08:37.640 align:middle line:84%
But if you go back in time
about 14 billion years,

00:08:37.640 --> 00:08:39.900 align:middle line:84%
then it all looks like
everything was extremely close

00:08:39.900 --> 00:08:40.700 align:middle line:90%
together.

00:08:40.700 --> 00:08:41.510 align:middle line:84%
And that's what we
call the Big Bang.

00:08:41.510 --> 00:08:42.289 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: And do
you think it was?

00:08:42.289 --> 00:08:43.220 align:middle line:90%
>>LISI: Yes.

00:08:43.220 --> 00:08:46.190 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, the evidence for Big
Bang now is incontrovertible.

00:08:46.190 --> 00:08:49.490 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: What causes
the expansion?

00:08:49.490 --> 00:08:53.290 align:middle line:84%
>>LISI: Well, so matter
itself gravitates.

00:08:53.290 --> 00:08:56.480 align:middle line:84%
So you would think matter
would bring everything back in.

00:08:56.480 --> 00:08:58.970 align:middle line:84%
And 50 years ago the
predominant theory

00:08:58.970 --> 00:09:00.590 align:middle line:84%
was that we had
a closed universe

00:09:00.590 --> 00:09:03.290 align:middle line:84%
where there was some
initial expansion

00:09:03.290 --> 00:09:07.220 align:middle line:84%
but that the gravitational pull
would pull everything back in.

00:09:07.220 --> 00:09:12.080 align:middle line:84%
But we looked out into space
and only about 15 years ago

00:09:12.080 --> 00:09:15.140 align:middle line:84%
discovered that not only is
matter not putting itself back

00:09:15.140 --> 00:09:19.130 align:middle line:84%
in but it's actually
accelerating out faster.

00:09:19.130 --> 00:09:20.180 align:middle line:90%
And that was a shock.

00:09:20.180 --> 00:09:22.100 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: How far out can it go?

00:09:22.100 --> 00:09:23.810 align:middle line:84%
>>LISI: There's
no limit, George.

00:09:23.810 --> 00:09:25.240 align:middle line:90%
So it can expand out forever.

00:09:25.240 --> 00:09:26.210 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: That's what's
so bizarre to me.

00:09:26.210 --> 00:09:27.670 align:middle line:84%
>>LISI: Right,
there are infinities

00:09:27.670 --> 00:09:29.810 align:middle line:90%
all over our universe.

00:09:29.810 --> 00:09:33.650 align:middle line:84%
It looks like our universe
will expand out forever in time

00:09:33.650 --> 00:09:35.329 align:middle line:90%
and forever in space.

00:09:35.329 --> 00:09:37.120 align:middle line:84%
As far as we can tell,
this is how it work.

00:09:37.120 --> 00:09:41.510 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: And newer systems
are being created and born,

00:09:41.510 --> 00:09:42.470 align:middle line:90%
new star systems--

00:09:42.470 --> 00:09:43.360 align:middle line:90%
>>LISI: New star systems--

00:09:43.360 --> 00:09:43.470 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: --new solar systems?

00:09:43.470 --> 00:09:44.511 align:middle line:90%
>>LISI: --are being born.

00:09:44.511 --> 00:09:47.300 align:middle line:84%
However with this
expansion, as these stars

00:09:47.300 --> 00:09:52.850 align:middle line:84%
are born they burn hydrogen.
They fuse hydrogen and helium.

00:09:52.850 --> 00:09:56.210 align:middle line:84%
And this is where the nuclear
fuel that fuels our sun

00:09:56.210 --> 00:09:57.820 align:middle line:90%
comes from and other stars.

00:09:57.820 --> 00:09:58.630 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: They'll
burn out one day.

00:09:58.630 --> 00:09:59.690 align:middle line:90%
>>LISI: They'll burn out.

00:09:59.690 --> 00:10:00.260 align:middle line:90%
So they burn out.

00:10:00.260 --> 00:10:01.160 align:middle line:90%
They go supernova.

00:10:01.160 --> 00:10:02.240 align:middle line:90%
They form other stars.

00:10:02.240 --> 00:10:03.440 align:middle line:90%
Those burn out.

00:10:03.440 --> 00:10:05.634 align:middle line:90%
They form black holes.

00:10:05.634 --> 00:10:06.800 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: When they burn out.

00:10:06.800 --> 00:10:10.280 align:middle line:84%
>>LISI: After they burn out,
they attract gravitationally.

00:10:10.280 --> 00:10:12.547 align:middle line:84%
Within galaxies, we'll
have giant black holes

00:10:12.547 --> 00:10:13.505 align:middle line:90%
formed within galaxies.

00:10:13.505 --> 00:10:15.046 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Basically
they're sucked in.

00:10:15.046 --> 00:10:17.270 align:middle line:84%
>>LISI: Yep, but
then those radiate.

00:10:17.270 --> 00:10:19.850 align:middle line:84%
So Hawking figured out
that black holes actually

00:10:19.850 --> 00:10:21.740 align:middle line:90%
emit radiation.

00:10:21.740 --> 00:10:24.750 align:middle line:84%
That radiation goes out into the
universe and then just expands.

00:10:24.750 --> 00:10:27.380 align:middle line:84%
So that all that matter that
was sucked into the black hole

00:10:27.380 --> 00:10:29.727 align:middle line:84%
goes away and you just
have radiation coming out.

00:10:29.727 --> 00:10:31.560 align:middle line:84%
And that happens
everywhere in the universe.

00:10:31.560 --> 00:10:33.890 align:middle line:84%
So if you go down the line
trillions and trillions

00:10:33.890 --> 00:10:36.320 align:middle line:84%
of years, you have
nothing in the universe

00:10:36.320 --> 00:10:38.430 align:middle line:84%
but dark blackness, and
that's all there is.

00:10:38.430 --> 00:10:39.680 align:middle line:90%
There's nothing else going on.

00:10:39.680 --> 00:10:41.596 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Hawking also
says though the universe

00:10:41.596 --> 00:10:42.560 align:middle line:90%
is going to burn out.

00:10:42.560 --> 00:10:44.080 align:middle line:84%
>>LISI: This is what
it means to burn out.

00:10:44.080 --> 00:10:45.746 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: OK, there
will be nothing left,

00:10:45.746 --> 00:10:47.473 align:middle line:90%
total darkness one day.

00:10:47.473 --> 00:10:51.191 align:middle line:84%
The last star, the last
person, shut the light off.

00:10:51.191 --> 00:10:52.940 align:middle line:84%
>>LISI: Yeah, that's
exactly what happens.

00:10:52.940 --> 00:10:54.440 align:middle line:90%
So this is our future.

00:10:54.440 --> 00:10:55.730 align:middle line:90%
It's not a very bright future.

00:10:55.730 --> 00:10:59.300 align:middle line:84%
But trillions and trillions of
years, that's a lot of time--

00:10:59.300 --> 00:11:00.750 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Like dead universe.

00:11:00.750 --> 00:11:03.422 align:middle line:84%
>>LISI: That's where things are
heading, yes, I'm afraid so.

00:11:03.422 --> 00:11:04.880 align:middle line:84%
That's what our
cosmology tells us.

00:11:04.880 --> 00:11:07.230 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: But other ones are
being born, other universes?

00:11:07.230 --> 00:11:09.740 align:middle line:84%
Do you believe in the
multiverse theory?

00:11:09.740 --> 00:11:12.200 align:middle line:84%
>>LISI: I don't
believe in anything.

00:11:12.200 --> 00:11:16.910 align:middle line:84%
I mean as a physicist, I have
degrees of belief in things.

00:11:16.910 --> 00:11:18.950 align:middle line:90%
So you flip a coin.

00:11:18.950 --> 00:11:21.440 align:middle line:84%
So you flip a coin
and you look at it

00:11:21.440 --> 00:11:23.600 align:middle line:84%
and before you
remove your hand you

00:11:23.600 --> 00:11:25.640 align:middle line:84%
have some confidence
that it's heads or tails.

00:11:25.640 --> 00:11:28.580 align:middle line:84%
And you have to have a
50% likelihood of each

00:11:28.580 --> 00:11:29.990 align:middle line:90%
if you have a reasonable coin.

00:11:29.990 --> 00:11:32.182 align:middle line:84%
You also have to have the
likelihood that, look,

00:11:32.182 --> 00:11:33.390 align:middle line:90%
there's no coin there at all.

00:11:33.390 --> 00:11:36.560 align:middle line:84%
There's also always
the weird option.

00:11:36.560 --> 00:11:38.340 align:middle line:84%
But for the most
part, as a physicist,

00:11:38.340 --> 00:11:40.450 align:middle line:84%
you have degrees of
belief in things.

00:11:40.450 --> 00:11:43.370 align:middle line:84%
Personally, I don't
have a high degree

00:11:43.370 --> 00:11:45.950 align:middle line:84%
of belief in other
universes being

00:11:45.950 --> 00:11:49.550 align:middle line:84%
born because we don't have good
mathematical models for it.

00:11:49.550 --> 00:11:52.290 align:middle line:84%
Philosophically, it's
not a terrible idea.

00:11:52.290 --> 00:11:54.512 align:middle line:84%
But scientifically, it
doesn't have a lot of content.

00:11:54.512 --> 00:11:55.970 align:middle line:84%
We can't test it
one way or another

00:11:55.970 --> 00:11:59.050 align:middle line:84%
since we can only do
tests in this universe.

00:11:59.050 --> 00:12:01.080 align:middle line:84%
So it's borderline
whether it's even science

00:12:01.080 --> 00:12:02.930 align:middle line:84%
to consider instances
of other universes.

00:12:02.930 --> 00:12:04.644 align:middle line:84%
But as a philosophical
idea, it's

00:12:04.644 --> 00:12:06.060 align:middle line:84%
certainly interesting
to consider.

00:12:06.060 --> 00:12:09.990 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Well how in the
world, Garrett, did it start?

00:12:09.990 --> 00:12:11.350 align:middle line:90%
>>LISI: Well, if you go back--

00:12:11.350 --> 00:12:14.100 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Are we bringing
God into the equation here?

00:12:14.100 --> 00:12:16.320 align:middle line:84%
>>LISI: If by we you mean
the royal we of you--

00:12:16.320 --> 00:12:16.920 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: You and me--

00:12:16.920 --> 00:12:17.720 align:middle line:90%
you and me.

00:12:17.720 --> 00:12:19.600 align:middle line:84%
>>LISI: --then you
can, but I'm not.

00:12:19.600 --> 00:12:20.400 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Not, OK.

00:12:20.400 --> 00:12:21.360 align:middle line:90%
We'll get into that--

00:12:21.360 --> 00:12:21.930 align:middle line:90%
>>LISI: We can get into that.

00:12:21.930 --> 00:12:23.055 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: --in a moment too.

00:12:23.055 --> 00:12:24.180 align:middle line:90%
But in your opinion--

00:12:24.180 --> 00:12:25.090 align:middle line:90%
>>LISI: In my personal opinion--

00:12:25.090 --> 00:12:25.380 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: --how did it start?

00:12:25.380 --> 00:12:26.970 align:middle line:90%
I mean, my god.

00:12:26.970 --> 00:12:29.760 align:middle line:84%
>>LISI: Yeah, and it's
funny, you fall back

00:12:29.760 --> 00:12:32.320 align:middle line:90%
to using my god as the answer.

00:12:32.320 --> 00:12:34.300 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: It's an
easy solution, right?

00:12:34.300 --> 00:12:35.670 align:middle line:90%
You blame it on god.

00:12:35.670 --> 00:12:36.960 align:middle line:90%
>>LISI: Right, god did it.

00:12:36.960 --> 00:12:39.090 align:middle line:84%
It's always the easiest
solution until you have

00:12:39.090 --> 00:12:40.530 align:middle line:90%
to explain where she came from.

00:12:40.530 --> 00:12:44.940 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: That's
right, or he, or it.

00:12:44.940 --> 00:12:48.300 align:middle line:84%
>>LISI: So if you follow the
expansion of the universe

00:12:48.300 --> 00:12:50.340 align:middle line:84%
and you go back in
time 14 trillion years

00:12:50.340 --> 00:12:55.260 align:middle line:84%
or so to where it was very
hot, it's not impossible

00:12:55.260 --> 00:12:58.830 align:middle line:84%
that you can just keep going
back in time before the Big

00:12:58.830 --> 00:12:59.850 align:middle line:90%
Bang.

00:12:59.850 --> 00:13:03.510 align:middle line:84%
And you can actually have
models for our universe

00:13:03.510 --> 00:13:06.270 align:middle line:84%
where it expands
indefinitely forever in time.

00:13:06.270 --> 00:13:07.990 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Which is
what you think.

00:13:07.990 --> 00:13:09.050 align:middle line:84%
>>LISI: I personally
hold that opinion.

00:13:09.050 --> 00:13:10.758 align:middle line:84%
I have a higher degree
of belief in that.

00:13:10.758 --> 00:13:14.080 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: But that still
doesn't explain how it started.

00:13:14.080 --> 00:13:16.267 align:middle line:84%
>>LISI: It wouldn't
have had a beginning.

00:13:16.267 --> 00:13:17.850 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Everything
needs a beginning.

00:13:17.850 --> 00:13:19.590 align:middle line:84%
>>LISI: That's because
we're used to existing

00:13:19.590 --> 00:13:20.580 align:middle line:90%
in this flow of time.

00:13:20.580 --> 00:13:22.510 align:middle line:84%
We're used to our
personal flow of time.

00:13:22.510 --> 00:13:23.310 align:middle line:90%
We're born.

00:13:23.310 --> 00:13:24.070 align:middle line:90%
Things happen.

00:13:24.070 --> 00:13:24.870 align:middle line:90%
We see that.

00:13:24.870 --> 00:13:27.609 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Yes, I'm thinking in
very logical stages of time.

00:13:27.609 --> 00:13:29.400 align:middle line:84%
>>LISI: Well, in this
model of the universe

00:13:29.400 --> 00:13:31.660 align:middle line:84%
there always would
have been a before.

00:13:31.660 --> 00:13:32.040 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: So you're saying--

00:13:32.040 --> 00:13:34.123 align:middle line:84%
>>LISI: Whatever there is,
there would have been a

00:13:34.123 --> 00:13:36.980 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: --that whatever
happened to the expansion,

00:13:36.980 --> 00:13:38.490 align:middle line:90%
it was there.

00:13:38.490 --> 00:13:42.020 align:middle line:90%
It was always there.

00:13:42.020 --> 00:13:44.064 align:middle line:90%
But how did it get there?

00:13:44.064 --> 00:13:45.480 align:middle line:84%
>>LISI: Well, this
is the question

00:13:45.480 --> 00:13:47.440 align:middle line:90%
of what is the universe?

00:13:47.440 --> 00:13:51.840 align:middle line:84%
So if you consider that time
extended forever before the Big

00:13:51.840 --> 00:13:56.490 align:middle line:84%
Bang and it will extend
forever into our future,

00:13:56.490 --> 00:13:59.280 align:middle line:84%
then you can look at this
as a whole in spacetime

00:13:59.280 --> 00:14:03.435 align:middle line:90%
as one whole thing in spacetime.

00:14:03.435 --> 00:14:06.360 align:middle line:84%
The name of this is called
the block universe model.

00:14:06.360 --> 00:14:08.650 align:middle line:90%
You look at it as a whole.

00:14:08.650 --> 00:14:10.200 align:middle line:84%
Now if you look at
this as a whole,

00:14:10.200 --> 00:14:14.064 align:middle line:84%
it looks like a
four-dimensional hyperbola

00:14:14.064 --> 00:14:15.980 align:middle line:84%
where you have something
expanding for forever

00:14:15.980 --> 00:14:18.250 align:middle line:84%
and then out like a
giant expanding horn.

00:14:18.250 --> 00:14:20.000 align:middle line:84%
It looks like a
four-dimensional hyperbola

00:14:20.000 --> 00:14:23.180 align:middle line:84%
where our spatial slices
are flat but expanding.

00:14:23.180 --> 00:14:25.670 align:middle line:84%
So it looks sort of
like a big giant horn

00:14:25.670 --> 00:14:28.250 align:middle line:84%
in four dimensions-- of
four-dimensional space,

00:14:28.250 --> 00:14:29.760 align:middle line:90%
not in four dimensions.

00:14:29.760 --> 00:14:34.460 align:middle line:84%
So if you look at this,
this is a familiar geometry.

00:14:34.460 --> 00:14:36.620 align:middle line:84%
It goes by the
name of someone who

00:14:36.620 --> 00:14:38.030 align:middle line:90%
described it named de Sitter.

00:14:38.030 --> 00:14:40.400 align:middle line:90%
So it's a de Sitter spacetime.

00:14:40.400 --> 00:14:42.550 align:middle line:84%
And it turns out a
de Sitter spacetime

00:14:42.550 --> 00:14:45.950 align:middle line:84%
can be described as a
four-dimensional surface

00:14:45.950 --> 00:14:50.380 align:middle line:84%
inside a larger mathematical
geometry called a Lie group.

00:14:50.380 --> 00:14:51.760 align:middle line:84%
So you can describe
this geometry

00:14:51.760 --> 00:14:53.656 align:middle line:90%
inside other geometries.

00:14:53.656 --> 00:14:55.030 align:middle line:84%
And these are the
same geometries

00:14:55.030 --> 00:14:56.830 align:middle line:84%
that are used to describe
particle physics.

00:14:56.830 --> 00:14:59.500 align:middle line:84%
If we model it this
way, we can see

00:14:59.500 --> 00:15:02.050 align:middle line:84%
our cosmological,
four-dimensional spacetime

00:15:02.050 --> 00:15:07.280 align:middle line:84%
universe as existing inside
a Lie group that is excited,

00:15:07.280 --> 00:15:08.080 align:middle line:90%
that's deforming.

00:15:08.080 --> 00:15:12.400 align:middle line:84%
The idea is you have to start
with some ultimate object.

00:15:12.400 --> 00:15:16.540 align:middle line:90%
So there has to be something.

00:15:16.540 --> 00:15:20.770 align:middle line:84%
So to start with something--
it's very satisfying to me

00:15:20.770 --> 00:15:24.340 align:middle line:84%
to start with the most
beautiful mathematical geometric

00:15:24.340 --> 00:15:26.980 align:middle line:90%
structure you can consider.

00:15:26.980 --> 00:15:29.450 align:middle line:84%
It's this
high-dimensional, twisting,

00:15:29.450 --> 00:15:33.430 align:middle line:84%
very intricately twisted knot
of beautiful, high-dimensional

00:15:33.430 --> 00:15:35.350 align:middle line:90%
geometry.

00:15:35.350 --> 00:15:40.270 align:middle line:84%
And then see that inside that
are all the subgeometries

00:15:40.270 --> 00:15:42.520 align:middle line:84%
we need to describe
particle physics

00:15:42.520 --> 00:15:45.820 align:middle line:84%
and to embed our
four-dimensional universe.

00:15:45.820 --> 00:15:47.830 align:middle line:84%
And then if that
somehow got excited

00:15:47.830 --> 00:15:51.100 align:middle line:84%
in a quantum-mechanical
way, then we

00:15:51.100 --> 00:15:54.680 align:middle line:84%
could see all the interactions
happening that we see around us

00:15:54.680 --> 00:15:55.480 align:middle line:90%
in our universe.

00:15:55.480 --> 00:15:57.910 align:middle line:84%
We can model that, but we
have to start with something.

00:15:57.910 --> 00:16:01.300 align:middle line:84%
So for me, philosophically,
it's more satisfying--

00:16:01.300 --> 00:16:04.870 align:middle line:84%
I have a higher degree of belief
that our universe fundamentally

00:16:04.870 --> 00:16:07.660 align:middle line:84%
is a very beautiful
high-dimensional geometric

00:16:07.660 --> 00:16:10.119 align:middle line:84%
object that has become excited
in a quantum-mechanical way.

00:16:10.119 --> 00:16:10.993 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Interesting.

00:16:10.993 --> 00:16:12.835 align:middle line:84%
10 years ago you spoke
at a TED conference.

00:16:12.835 --> 00:16:15.310 align:middle line:90%
>>LISI: Yes.

00:16:15.310 --> 00:16:18.850 align:middle line:84%
This particular pattern of
charges in eight dimensions

00:16:18.850 --> 00:16:21.400 align:middle line:84%
is actually part of the most
beautiful geometric structure

00:16:21.400 --> 00:16:23.560 align:middle line:90%
in mathematics.

00:16:23.560 --> 00:16:27.550 align:middle line:84%
It's a pattern of the largest
exceptional Lie group E8.

00:16:27.550 --> 00:16:29.590 align:middle line:10%
This Lie group is a
smooth curved shape

00:16:29.590 --> 00:16:31.570 align:middle line:10%
with 248 dimensions.

00:16:31.570 --> 00:16:33.850 align:middle line:84%
Each point in this
pattern corresponds

00:16:33.850 --> 00:16:37.540 align:middle line:84%
to a symmetry of this very
complex and beautiful shape.

00:16:37.540 --> 00:16:39.610 align:middle line:84%
One small part of
this E8 shape can

00:16:39.610 --> 00:16:41.890 align:middle line:84%
be used to describe the
curved spacetime of Einstein's

00:16:41.890 --> 00:16:45.010 align:middle line:84%
general relativity,
explaining gravity.

00:16:45.010 --> 00:16:47.741 align:middle line:84%
Together with quantum mechanics,
the geometry of this shape

00:16:47.741 --> 00:16:49.990 align:middle line:84%
could describe everything
about how the universe works

00:16:49.990 --> 00:16:51.720 align:middle line:90%
at the tiniest scales.

00:16:51.720 --> 00:16:53.920 align:middle line:10%
And the pattern of
the shape, living

00:16:53.920 --> 00:16:56.140 align:middle line:10%
in eight-dimensional
charge space,

00:16:56.140 --> 00:16:58.840 align:middle line:10%
is exquisitely beautiful.

00:16:58.840 --> 00:17:01.030 align:middle line:84%
And it summarizes thousands
of possible interactions

00:17:01.030 --> 00:17:03.071 align:middle line:84%
between these elementary
particles, each of which

00:17:03.071 --> 00:17:07.026 align:middle line:84%
is just a facet of
this complicated shape.

00:17:07.026 --> 00:17:09.609 align:middle line:10%
As we spin it, we can see many
of the other intricate patterns

00:17:09.609 --> 00:17:12.838 align:middle line:10%
contained in this one.

00:17:12.838 --> 00:17:15.094 align:middle line:10%
And with a, particular
rotation, we

00:17:15.094 --> 00:17:16.510 align:middle line:10%
can look down
through this pattern

00:17:16.510 --> 00:17:19.300 align:middle line:10%
in eight dimensions
along our symmetry axis

00:17:19.300 --> 00:17:21.130 align:middle line:10%
and see all the
particles at once.

00:17:21.130 --> 00:17:22.750 align:middle line:10%
It's a very beautiful object.

00:17:22.750 --> 00:17:26.079 align:middle line:10%
And, as with any unification,
we can see some holes

00:17:26.079 --> 00:17:29.680 align:middle line:10%
