in the past few years
I've been working on it,

00:26:22.960 --> 00:26:24.550 align:middle line:84%
but it's sufficiently
inspiring that I

00:26:24.550 --> 00:26:27.520 align:middle line:84%
think something there is right,
which is what I'm pursuing.

00:26:27.520 --> 00:26:30.400 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: If you had a chance to
have met and discussed things

00:26:30.400 --> 00:26:33.520 align:middle line:84%
with Albert Einstein, what
would you have asked him?

00:26:33.520 --> 00:26:34.704 align:middle line:90%
>>LISI: Oh wow.

00:26:34.704 --> 00:26:36.370 align:middle line:84%
Sure, I would have
loved the opportunity

00:26:36.370 --> 00:26:39.010 align:middle line:90%
to talk with Einstein.

00:26:39.010 --> 00:26:43.090 align:middle line:84%
I mean, he passed
away in late '50s,

00:26:43.090 --> 00:26:47.667 align:middle line:84%
and he passed away right before
a real explosion in knowledge

00:26:47.667 --> 00:26:48.500 align:middle line:90%
of particle physics.

00:26:48.500 --> 00:26:50.557 align:middle line:10%
>>NOORY: And he did all
this without a computer.

00:26:50.557 --> 00:26:51.640 align:middle line:10%
>>LISI: Yeah, it was all--

00:26:51.640 --> 00:26:52.473 align:middle line:10%
>>NOORY: Chalkboard.

00:26:52.473 --> 00:26:55.160 align:middle line:10%
>>LISI: --chalkboard,
pencil and paper.

00:26:55.160 --> 00:27:00.197 align:middle line:84%
But he never really got to
see our current knowledge

00:27:00.197 --> 00:27:01.030 align:middle line:90%
of particle physics.

00:27:01.030 --> 00:27:02.435 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Would he be impressed?

00:27:02.435 --> 00:27:04.060 align:middle line:84%
>>LISI: He'd be
impressed but he'd also

00:27:04.060 --> 00:27:06.010 align:middle line:90%
be pretty baffled at first.

00:27:06.010 --> 00:27:08.074 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Would he
be proven right?

00:27:08.074 --> 00:27:10.240 align:middle line:84%
>>LISI: He has been proven
right over and over again

00:27:10.240 --> 00:27:12.400 align:middle line:90%
for his theory of gravity.

00:27:12.400 --> 00:27:14.242 align:middle line:84%
But there were so many
elementary particles,

00:27:14.242 --> 00:27:16.450 align:middle line:84%
the whole structure of the
standard model of particle

00:27:16.450 --> 00:27:22.510 align:middle line:84%
physics, like the weak force was
just starting to be considered.

00:27:22.510 --> 00:27:25.930 align:middle line:84%
And Gell-Mann had not come out
with his Lie group description

00:27:25.930 --> 00:27:27.220 align:middle line:90%
of the strong force yet.

00:27:27.220 --> 00:27:30.430 align:middle line:84%
So Einstein passed away before
we knew most of modern particle

00:27:30.430 --> 00:27:31.540 align:middle line:90%
physics.

00:27:31.540 --> 00:27:33.706 align:middle line:84%
And quantum-field theory
had been developed but just

00:27:33.706 --> 00:27:35.796 align:middle line:90%
to a very minimal degree.

00:27:35.796 --> 00:27:38.170 align:middle line:84%
And we didn't have this whole
zoo of elementary particles

00:27:38.170 --> 00:27:39.400 align:middle line:90%
that we now know about.

00:27:39.400 --> 00:27:41.590 align:middle line:84%
So I would have
asked Einstein what

00:27:41.590 --> 00:27:45.100 align:middle line:84%
he would make of this zoo
of elementary particles

00:27:45.100 --> 00:27:47.290 align:middle line:84%
in the context of his theory
of general relativity.

00:27:47.290 --> 00:27:48.665 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Well
Garrett, what would

00:27:48.665 --> 00:27:51.130 align:middle line:84%
have caused this
explosion of knowledge

00:27:51.130 --> 00:27:55.480 align:middle line:84%
from the Einstein days
to where we are now?

00:27:55.480 --> 00:27:57.040 align:middle line:90%
What happened?

00:27:57.040 --> 00:28:00.140 align:middle line:84%
>>LISI: There were two
things that happened.

00:28:00.140 --> 00:28:04.180 align:middle line:84%
One was the development in
mathematics of Yang-Mills

00:28:04.180 --> 00:28:07.332 align:middle line:84%
theory or the idea of
Ehresmann connections

00:28:07.332 --> 00:28:09.790 align:middle line:84%
and principal bundles which
are these abstract mathematical

00:28:09.790 --> 00:28:15.100 align:middle line:84%
things and basically
the use of Lie groups

00:28:15.100 --> 00:28:17.560 align:middle line:90%
to describe complex geometries.

00:28:17.560 --> 00:28:19.670 align:middle line:90%
So that happened in mathematics.

00:28:19.670 --> 00:28:21.580 align:middle line:84%
So Einstein knew
about Lie groups,

00:28:21.580 --> 00:28:24.592 align:middle line:84%
and he actually talked to
a friend of mine about them

00:28:24.592 --> 00:28:26.175 align:middle line:84%
shortly before he
passed away, thought

00:28:26.175 --> 00:28:27.716 align:middle line:84%
they were a very
interesting subject.

00:28:27.716 --> 00:28:29.440 align:middle line:84%
But he didn't have
time to investigate

00:28:29.440 --> 00:28:31.480 align:middle line:84%
that area of mathematics
because it was so new,

00:28:31.480 --> 00:28:34.180 align:middle line:84%
and it was just starting to
be considered for physics.

00:28:34.180 --> 00:28:36.096 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Einstein
believed in God.

00:28:36.096 --> 00:28:36.970 align:middle line:90%
>>LISI: No he didn't.

00:28:36.970 --> 00:28:37.990 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: I think he did.

00:28:37.990 --> 00:28:40.150 align:middle line:84%
>>LISI: No, there's
no indication he--

00:28:40.150 --> 00:28:41.920 align:middle line:84%
and he made reference
to something

00:28:41.920 --> 00:28:43.210 align:middle line:90%
like Spinoza's god which is--

00:28:43.210 --> 00:28:44.460 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Want a do over there?

00:28:44.460 --> 00:28:46.480 align:middle line:90%
>>LISI: --the god of nature.

00:28:46.480 --> 00:28:48.940 align:middle line:84%
So he referred to
god as nature, which

00:28:48.940 --> 00:28:51.340 align:middle line:84%
is sort of an amorphous,
impersonal way of considering

00:28:51.340 --> 00:28:52.140 align:middle line:90%
the universe.

00:28:52.140 --> 00:28:54.869 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Yeah, but
it was something.

00:28:54.869 --> 00:28:57.160 align:middle line:84%
>>LISI: It was something but
it wasn't a supreme being.

00:28:57.160 --> 00:28:58.910 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: I mean, I
don't know what God is.

00:28:58.910 --> 00:29:01.660 align:middle line:84%
All I know is there's
something there

00:29:01.660 --> 00:29:05.200 align:middle line:84%
that has helped jump
start all of this.

00:29:05.200 --> 00:29:07.690 align:middle line:84%
I don't believe-- and I
was raised a Catholic.

00:29:07.690 --> 00:29:10.030 align:middle line:84%
I don't believe in
some guy sitting

00:29:10.030 --> 00:29:14.260 align:middle line:84%
in a throne in the clouds,
which is how they taught us what

00:29:14.260 --> 00:29:16.870 align:middle line:90%
God was in catechism classes.

00:29:16.870 --> 00:29:20.940 align:middle line:84%
I don't believe that
at all, anymore.

00:29:20.940 --> 00:29:21.760 align:middle line:90%
I don't know.

00:29:21.760 --> 00:29:23.470 align:middle line:90%
I don't know what it is.

00:29:23.470 --> 00:29:25.990 align:middle line:84%
If I were interviewing
the pope today,

00:29:25.990 --> 00:29:27.880 align:middle line:84%
I'm not sure he could
give me a good answer.

00:29:27.880 --> 00:29:30.760 align:middle line:90%


00:29:30.760 --> 00:29:34.330 align:middle line:84%
>>LISI: It's a different
kind of model for reality.

00:29:34.330 --> 00:29:36.430 align:middle line:84%
Personally, I find
scientific models of reality

00:29:36.430 --> 00:29:37.720 align:middle line:90%
much more satisfying.

00:29:37.720 --> 00:29:42.220 align:middle line:84%
I am very happy with mathematics
and mathematical descriptions.

00:29:42.220 --> 00:29:43.780 align:middle line:90%
They're precise.

00:29:43.780 --> 00:29:46.990 align:middle line:84%
And they are extraordinarily
successful for describing

00:29:46.990 --> 00:29:50.020 align:middle line:84%
what happens when we
attempt to apply that.

00:29:50.020 --> 00:29:51.460 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Somewhere
along the line

00:29:51.460 --> 00:29:56.800 align:middle line:84%
the physicist Garrett
decided to change.

00:29:56.800 --> 00:30:01.000 align:middle line:84%
And you picked up and
moved to Maui, surfed.

00:30:01.000 --> 00:30:03.430 align:middle line:84%
What caused that
metamorphosis for you?

00:30:03.430 --> 00:30:05.425 align:middle line:84%
I mean, did you
give up on science?

00:30:05.425 --> 00:30:09.610 align:middle line:84%
>>LISI: Oh, it was
the exact opposite.

00:30:09.610 --> 00:30:13.420 align:middle line:84%
So when I got my PhD,
rather than go and get

00:30:13.420 --> 00:30:19.000 align:middle line:84%
a postdoc somewhere and continue
climbing the academic ladder,

00:30:19.000 --> 00:30:20.680 align:middle line:84%
I decided I could
more thoroughly

00:30:20.680 --> 00:30:23.409 align:middle line:84%
devote myself to
scientific investigation

00:30:23.409 --> 00:30:25.450 align:middle line:84%
if I just went to an island
and worked by myself.

00:30:25.450 --> 00:30:28.330 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: All right,
so you did this.

00:30:28.330 --> 00:30:30.400 align:middle line:90%
What did you do for a living?

00:30:30.400 --> 00:30:31.554 align:middle line:90%
How did you exist?

00:30:31.554 --> 00:30:32.470 align:middle line:90%
>>LISI: Good question.

00:30:32.470 --> 00:30:34.870 align:middle line:90%
Why didn't I starve?

00:30:34.870 --> 00:30:36.700 align:middle line:90%
What had happened is--

00:30:36.700 --> 00:30:41.260 align:middle line:84%
well first of all, academia,
you have to understand,

00:30:41.260 --> 00:30:43.910 align:middle line:84%
is in a very strange
situation right now.

00:30:43.910 --> 00:30:47.470 align:middle line:84%
And it's in that situation
because of the way economics

00:30:47.470 --> 00:30:49.540 align:middle line:90%
work within academia.

00:30:49.540 --> 00:30:51.610 align:middle line:84%
There's a demand
for cheap labor.

00:30:51.610 --> 00:30:54.890 align:middle line:84%
And cheap labor in academia
is graduate students.

00:30:54.890 --> 00:30:57.032 align:middle line:84%
So what happens is
for the people who

00:30:57.032 --> 00:30:59.240 align:middle line:84%
graduate at the top of their
class as undergraduate--

00:30:59.240 --> 00:31:00.430 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: They grab
them, don't they?

00:31:00.430 --> 00:31:02.830 align:middle line:84%
>>LISI: Yeah, so I graduated
at the top of my class

00:31:02.830 --> 00:31:05.360 align:middle line:84%
as an undergraduate, and I got
invitations to go to schools,

00:31:05.360 --> 00:31:07.110 align:middle line:84%
and they were going
to throw money at me--

00:31:07.110 --> 00:31:08.710 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: As a
teacher, professor?

00:31:08.710 --> 00:31:10.912 align:middle line:84%
>>LISI: As a research
assistant and graduate student

00:31:10.912 --> 00:31:11.870 align:middle line:90%
and teaching assistant.

00:31:11.870 --> 00:31:12.920 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: And pay you?

00:31:12.920 --> 00:31:14.860 align:middle line:90%
>>LISI: So I got a good offer.

00:31:14.860 --> 00:31:16.930 align:middle line:90%
I went to UC San Diego.

00:31:16.930 --> 00:31:18.830 align:middle line:84%
And I also like
playing with computers.

00:31:18.830 --> 00:31:21.790 align:middle line:84%
I have ever since
I was a young kid.

00:31:21.790 --> 00:31:23.290 align:middle line:90%
So I took a bunch of this money.

00:31:23.290 --> 00:31:25.380 align:middle line:84%
I bought a really nice
computer called the NeXT.

00:31:25.380 --> 00:31:27.370 align:middle line:10%
The NeXT was the
computer company

00:31:27.370 --> 00:31:29.910 align:middle line:10%
started by Steve Jobs when
he was kicked out of Apple.

00:31:29.910 --> 00:31:31.900 align:middle line:10%
>>NOORY: And then
he came back again.

00:31:31.900 --> 00:31:34.660 align:middle line:10%
>>LISI: What happened was the
operating system for the NeXT

00:31:34.660 --> 00:31:37.470 align:middle line:10%
computer was based on Unix.

00:31:37.470 --> 00:31:39.910 align:middle line:90%
And this was in the '90s.

00:31:39.910 --> 00:31:43.190 align:middle line:84%
It was a great operating system,
very intuitive user interface,

00:31:43.190 --> 00:31:43.990 align:middle line:90%
worked great.

00:31:43.990 --> 00:31:47.970 align:middle line:84%
Apple, in the meantime,
was dealing with system 7,

00:31:47.970 --> 00:31:49.960 align:middle line:90%
Mac OS-- you know, system 7.

00:31:49.960 --> 00:31:51.010 align:middle line:90%
And it was just terrible.

00:31:51.010 --> 00:31:52.130 align:middle line:90%
And they didn't know what to do.

00:31:52.130 --> 00:31:53.230 align:middle line:84%
They needed a new
operating system.

00:31:53.230 --> 00:31:54.771 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: They needed
Steve Jobs back.

00:31:54.771 --> 00:31:55.970 align:middle line:90%
That's what they needed.

00:31:55.970 --> 00:31:59.020 align:middle line:84%
>>LISI: So what they did
is Apple bought NeXT.

00:31:59.020 --> 00:32:01.270 align:middle line:84%
But really what happened
is NeXT bought Apple

00:32:01.270 --> 00:32:04.630 align:middle line:84%
for a negative amount of money
because Steve Jobs became

00:32:04.630 --> 00:32:05.430 align:middle line:90%
the interim--

00:32:05.430 --> 00:32:05.950 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: He came
right back in again.

00:32:05.950 --> 00:32:06.750 align:middle line:90%
>>LISI: --CEO.

00:32:06.750 --> 00:32:10.000 align:middle line:84%
He put his people from NeXT
into the head of Apple now.

00:32:10.000 --> 00:32:12.010 align:middle line:84%
And now essentially
Apple became NeXT.

00:32:12.010 --> 00:32:16.030 align:middle line:84%
And the NeXTSTEP operating
system that I had been using,

00:32:16.030 --> 00:32:18.430 align:middle line:84%
I knew that was going to
become the new operating

00:32:18.430 --> 00:32:20.020 align:middle line:90%
system for Apple.

00:32:20.020 --> 00:32:21.746 align:middle line:84%
So I took all that
money that I'd been

00:32:21.746 --> 00:32:22.870 align:middle line:90%
given for graduate school--

00:32:22.870 --> 00:32:24.240 align:middle line:84%
because even though
I was cheap labor,

00:32:24.240 --> 00:32:25.660 align:middle line:84%
it was more money
than I'd ever seen.

00:32:25.660 --> 00:32:27.280 align:middle line:84%
I invested that in
Apple stock in the '90s

00:32:27.280 --> 00:32:28.270 align:middle line:84%
when everybody thought it was
going to go out of business.

00:32:28.270 --> 00:32:29.640 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: And you made
a home run with that.

00:32:29.640 --> 00:32:31.270 align:middle line:84%
>>LISI: Yeah, I made a
bunch of money out of it.

00:32:31.270 --> 00:32:32.410 align:middle line:84%
So that's what let
me move to Maui

00:32:32.410 --> 00:32:34.960 align:middle line:84%
and work on physics on my
own and be a surf bum instead

00:32:34.960 --> 00:32:35.920 align:middle line:90%
of going out to get a postdoc.

00:32:35.920 --> 00:32:37.753 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: So what did
you do with your money?

00:32:37.753 --> 00:32:39.580 align:middle line:84%
>>LISI: Well, over
the years I've

00:32:39.580 --> 00:32:41.740 align:middle line:90%
seen different waves coming.

00:32:41.740 --> 00:32:43.480 align:middle line:84%
So it was actually
when I was here

00:32:43.480 --> 00:32:48.220 align:middle line:84%
living in Colorado in Frisco
in Summit County trying out

00:32:48.220 --> 00:32:51.220 align:middle line:84%
being a snowbird bum
for a couple seasons.

00:32:51.220 --> 00:32:53.970 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Ski bum, a surfer bum.

00:32:53.970 --> 00:32:58.750 align:middle line:84%
>>LISI: And then I was really
enjoying using Netflix.

00:32:58.750 --> 00:33:01.390 align:middle line:84%
And I saw that Netflix was
well positioned, first of all,

00:33:01.390 --> 00:33:03.490 align:middle line:84%
to take advantage
of the postal system

00:33:03.490 --> 00:33:05.830 align:middle line:90%
for cheap mail of their DVDs.

00:33:05.830 --> 00:33:07.242 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: DVDs at the time.

00:33:07.242 --> 00:33:08.950 align:middle line:84%
>>LISI: And then also
they were very well

00:33:08.950 --> 00:33:11.020 align:middle line:84%
positioned to take
advantage of the internet,

00:33:11.020 --> 00:33:14.780 align:middle line:84%
to stream movies to people
for a very low cost.

00:33:14.780 --> 00:33:16.590 align:middle line:84%
So my next investment
was Netflix,

00:33:16.590 --> 00:33:18.520 align:middle line:90%
and I did quite well with that.

00:33:18.520 --> 00:33:22.810 align:middle line:84%
And then more recently
in around 2010

00:33:22.810 --> 00:33:26.650 align:middle line:84%
I caught wind of
this cryptocurrency,

00:33:26.650 --> 00:33:28.485 align:middle line:84%
this digital currency
called Bitcoin.

00:33:28.485 --> 00:33:30.860 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: I have questions
about that stuff, but go ahead.

00:33:30.860 --> 00:33:32.554 align:middle line:84%
>>LISI: That was
just getting started.

00:33:32.554 --> 00:33:33.970 align:middle line:84%
And so I put a
little bit of money

00:33:33.970 --> 00:33:38.350 align:middle line:84%
in Bitcoin because it seemed
like a really cool idea

00:33:38.350 --> 00:33:40.280 align:middle line:84%
and just sort of
let that sit there.

00:33:40.280 --> 00:33:41.710 align:middle line:90%
And it's been a while.

00:33:41.710 --> 00:33:43.870 align:middle line:90%
And that did unusually well.

00:33:43.870 --> 00:33:46.070 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: I don't think it's
going to hold its value.

00:33:46.070 --> 00:33:48.340 align:middle line:90%
What do you think, as of now?

00:33:48.340 --> 00:33:52.000 align:middle line:84%
>>LISI: At this point I'm
too scared to sell it.

00:33:52.000 --> 00:33:53.230 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Really?

00:33:53.230 --> 00:33:55.640 align:middle line:84%
You can make money if you
sold what you have now.

00:33:55.640 --> 00:33:56.440 align:middle line:90%
>>LISI: I could.

00:33:56.440 --> 00:34:00.280 align:middle line:84%
I don't have enough Bitcoin
to make me a good kidnapping

00:34:00.280 --> 00:34:02.270 align:middle line:90%
target.

00:34:02.270 --> 00:34:05.335 align:middle line:84%
I've got far less than
half a million dollars

00:34:05.335 --> 00:34:07.616 align:middle line:84%
of Bitcoin at current
valuation, far less than that.

00:34:07.616 --> 00:34:09.699 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: All right, well
let's take a look at what

00:34:09.699 --> 00:34:11.760 align:middle line:90%
cryptocurrency really is.

00:34:11.760 --> 00:34:14.382 align:middle line:84%
>>LISI: Certainly
happy to talk about it.

00:34:14.382 --> 00:34:16.760 align:middle line:84%
>>NARRATOR: There's
Bitcoin, there's Litecoin,

00:34:16.760 --> 00:34:18.010 align:middle line:90%
there's Ethereum.

00:34:18.010 --> 00:34:21.409 align:middle line:84%
So just what is cryptocurrency
and how does it work?

00:34:21.409 --> 00:34:25.520 align:middle line:84%
Essentially it's digital money
that is bought and sold online.

00:34:25.520 --> 00:34:27.730 align:middle line:10%
There are no bills
or coins, it's not

00:34:27.730 --> 00:34:29.949 align:middle line:10%
based on another
asset like gold,

00:34:29.949 --> 00:34:32.020 align:middle line:10%
and it doesn't go through
traditional financial

00:34:32.020 --> 00:34:34.420 align:middle line:10%
institutions like banks.

00:34:34.420 --> 00:34:36.429 align:middle line:10%
Instead, these
currencies operate

00:34:36.429 --> 00:34:38.650 align:middle line:10%
in a completely
decentralized system

00:34:38.650 --> 00:34:41.020 align:middle line:10%
that uses so-called
blockchain technology

00:34:41.020 --> 00:34:43.030 align:middle line:10%
to track transactions.

00:34:43.030 --> 00:34:45.580 align:middle line:84%
To see how this works, let's
look at how you buy something

00:34:45.580 --> 00:34:47.679 align:middle line:90%
with cryptocurrency.

00:34:47.679 --> 00:34:51.010 align:middle line:84%
Say that Alice wants to buy a
bike from Dan using Bitcoin,

00:34:51.010 --> 00:34:53.199 align:middle line:90%
her cryptocurrency of choice.

00:34:53.199 --> 00:34:55.659 align:middle line:84%
Alice begins by logging
into her Bitcoin wallet

00:34:55.659 --> 00:34:58.690 align:middle line:84%
with a private key, a unique
combination of letters

00:34:58.690 --> 00:35:00.280 align:middle line:90%
and numbers.

00:35:00.280 --> 00:35:02.680 align:middle line:84%
With a traditional
financial transaction,

00:35:02.680 --> 00:35:05.170 align:middle line:84%
the exchange gets sent
to banks on each side who

00:35:05.170 --> 00:35:07.630 align:middle line:84%
record the money being
subtracted from one account

00:35:07.630 --> 00:35:09.550 align:middle line:90%
and added to another.

00:35:09.550 --> 00:35:11.680 align:middle line:84%
But remember, in
this scenario, there

00:35:11.680 --> 00:35:13.750 align:middle line:90%
are no banks or middlemen.

00:35:13.750 --> 00:35:16.870 align:middle line:10%
Instead, Alice's transaction
is shared with everyone

00:35:16.870 --> 00:35:18.670 align:middle line:10%
in the Bitcoin network.

00:35:18.670 --> 00:35:21.230 align:middle line:84%
These networked computers
add Alice's transaction

00:35:21.230 --> 00:35:25.330 align:middle line:84%
to a shared list of recent
transactions known as a block.

00:35:25.330 --> 00:35:27.850 align:middle line:84%
Every 10 minutes, the
newest block of transactions

00:35:27.850 --> 00:35:31.690 align:middle line:84%
is added on or chained to
all the previous blocks.

00:35:31.690 --> 00:35:34.420 align:middle line:90%
That's how you get a blockchain.

00:35:34.420 --> 00:35:37.060 align:middle line:10%
To ensure that each block
of transactions on the chain

00:35:37.060 --> 00:35:39.580 align:middle line:10%
is verified, a subset
of Bitcoin's network

00:35:39.580 --> 00:35:42.880 align:middle line:10%
joins a race to solve a
very difficult math puzzle.

00:35:42.880 --> 00:35:45.400 align:middle line:84%
And if they solve it
first, their record

00:35:45.400 --> 00:35:48.700 align:middle line:84%
of the block of transactions
becomes the official record.

00:35:48.700 --> 00:35:50.920 align:middle line:84%
They're rewarded with
bitcoins of their own

00:35:50.920 --> 00:35:54.160 align:middle line:84%
and the network gets a
new block on the chain.

00:35:54.160 --> 00:35:56.710 align:middle line:84%
This entire process
is known as mining,

00:35:56.710 --> 00:35:58.420 align:middle line:84%
but instead of
chipping away at rock,

00:35:58.420 --> 00:36:00.880 align:middle line:90%
you're solving complex puzzles.

00:36:00.880 --> 00:36:04.300 align:middle line:84%
The fact that many computers
are competing to verify a block

00:36:04.300 --> 00:36:07.240 align:middle line:84%
ensures that no single computer
can monopolize the Bitcoin

00:36:07.240 --> 00:36:08.560 align:middle line:90%
market.

00:36:08.560 --> 00:36:11.740 align:middle line:84%
To ensure the competition
stays fair and evenly timed,

00:36:11.740 --> 00:36:15.550 align:middle line:84%
the puzzle becomes harder
when more computers join in.

00:36:15.550 --> 00:36:17.440 align:middle line:84%
The Bitcoin protocol
says mining will

00:36:17.440 --> 00:36:21.410 align:middle line:84%
continue until there are 21
million bitcoins in existence.

00:36:21.410 --> 00:36:24.010 align:middle line:84%
That's set to
happen around 2140,

00:36:24.010 --> 00:36:27.960 align:middle line:90%
if Bitcoin lasts that long.

