00:39:51.940 --> 00:39:54.370 align:middle line:90%
that goes into this pool.

00:39:54.370 --> 00:39:58.810 align:middle line:84%
And there are many thousands
of computers distributed

00:39:58.810 --> 00:40:01.789 align:middle line:84%
throughout the world who will
see my potential transaction as

00:40:01.789 --> 00:40:03.580 align:middle line:84%
well as a small fee
that I'm willing to pay

00:40:03.580 --> 00:40:05.634 align:middle line:90%
to make that transition happen.

00:40:05.634 --> 00:40:07.300 align:middle line:84%
And then they will
take that transaction

00:40:07.300 --> 00:40:11.320 align:middle line:84%
and put it in their block,
in their 1-megabyte block.

00:40:11.320 --> 00:40:16.430 align:middle line:84%
And then they will try to, as I
said, solve this math problem.

00:40:16.430 --> 00:40:19.450 align:middle line:84%
So what they're doing is they
take all these transactions

00:40:19.450 --> 00:40:22.360 align:middle line:84%
from the pool that people want
to make with their bitcoin.

00:40:22.360 --> 00:40:25.480 align:middle line:84%
And they get it in
their 1-megabyte block.

00:40:25.480 --> 00:40:28.130 align:middle line:84%
And then they use
what's called a hash.

00:40:28.130 --> 00:40:29.722 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Who's they?

00:40:29.722 --> 00:40:31.180 align:middle line:84%
>>LISI: All the
thousands of people

00:40:31.180 --> 00:40:33.250 align:middle line:84%
who are trying to
make money in Bitcoin.

00:40:33.250 --> 00:40:35.290 align:middle line:90%
They're trying to mine bitcoin.

00:40:35.290 --> 00:40:37.960 align:middle line:84%
So by doing this process,
the winner of this process

00:40:37.960 --> 00:40:40.310 align:middle line:90%
wins a few bitcoin.

00:40:40.310 --> 00:40:42.870 align:middle line:84%
And bitcoin is, as you
said, worth $7,000 or $8,000

00:40:42.870 --> 00:40:44.070 align:middle line:90%
a coin right now.

00:40:44.070 --> 00:40:47.290 align:middle line:84%
And they win a few if
they can win this search.

00:40:47.290 --> 00:40:49.510 align:middle line:84%
So basically they have
this 1-megabyte block

00:40:49.510 --> 00:40:50.766 align:middle line:90%
of transactions.

00:40:50.766 --> 00:40:52.390 align:middle line:84%
And they're looking
for a magic number.

00:40:52.390 --> 00:40:56.080 align:middle line:84%
That number is called
a nonce, which is

00:40:56.080 --> 00:40:57.754 align:middle line:90%
short for a number used once.

00:40:57.754 --> 00:40:59.170 align:middle line:84%
So they're looking
for this nonce.

00:40:59.170 --> 00:41:02.770 align:middle line:84%
It will be the magic nonce
such that when they combine it

00:41:02.770 --> 00:41:06.720 align:middle line:84%
in a formula that scrambles
this information reversibility,

00:41:06.720 --> 00:41:10.200 align:middle line:84%
it comes up with a certain
number of leading zeros.

00:41:10.200 --> 00:41:12.990 align:middle line:84%
So you have this 1 megabyte of
data which you can represent

00:41:12.990 --> 00:41:14.464 align:middle line:90%
in a computer as a number.

00:41:14.464 --> 00:41:16.380 align:middle line:84%
You combine it with a
number in a formula that

00:41:16.380 --> 00:41:21.610 align:middle line:84%
gives other data that's a
megabyte through a set formula.

00:41:21.610 --> 00:41:24.090 align:middle line:84%
And if that formula
and that nonce

00:41:24.090 --> 00:41:29.640 align:middle line:84%
produces a new set of data
with a set of leading zeros,

00:41:29.640 --> 00:41:33.840 align:middle line:84%
say 8 to 20 leading
zeros or something,

00:41:33.840 --> 00:41:35.395 align:middle line:90%
then they found the magic nonce.

00:41:35.395 --> 00:41:37.020 align:middle line:84%
And then they announce
that to the rest

00:41:37.020 --> 00:41:39.061 align:middle line:84%
of the network and they
are rewarded with bitcoin

00:41:39.061 --> 00:41:41.354 align:middle line:84%
and that 1 megabyte
of transaction

00:41:41.354 --> 00:41:42.270 align:middle line:90%
is added to the block.

